		<h4>Determining Design Requirements</h4>
		<p>
			Before starting the actual design process (of laying out concrete UI), I met with the team to kick off the project and align on some mobile-related topics. I presented some of my thoughts regarding the increasing importance of having a mobile-optimized site and a couple basic principles that would help guide the design:
		</p>
		<br>
		<h5>The importance of mobile.</h5>
		<p>Based on our site traffic, it was clear that enough users were accessing our site on mobile devices to warrant our attention.  This number of users was also growing over time â€“ which is very much in line with the plentiful research out there that shows that mobile usage is continually increasing (including e-commerce transactions) and never stops, regardless of the time or day of the week it is.</p>
		<br>
		<h5>The mobile mindset.</h5>
		<p>It would be important to always keep in mind the mindset of the mobile user, who:</p>
		<ul class="disc">
			<li><b>Multitasks:</b> Uses the phone for short bursts of activity (not complex multi-step processes)</li>
			<li><b>Uses Geolocation Services</b>: Finds out what's local/around them (in this case, store locators and deals would be relevant)</li>
			<li><b>Alleviates Boredom</b>: Uses the phone for distraction and entertainment</li>
		</ul>
		<p>Understanding this context would help inform the design, particularly in keeping it simple and minimal, and surfacing the most pertinent features to the user, given their limited time and attention.</p>
		<br>
		<h5>Compatible devices.</h5>
		<p>It was in the very beginning that we determined which devices we'd optimize the site for, both by checking the web analytics for device types of our past visitors, and also by checking out stats for <a href="http://gs.statcounter.com/#mobile_os-US-yearly-2010-2011">top mobile OSes for general web traffic</a>. We decided to optimize for three key platforms.
		</p>
	</div>
