		<h4>Low-Fidelity Wireframes</h4>
		<p>With a site hierarchy mapped out, I began designing low-fidelity wireframes for each key screen. The goal of these wireframes were to illustrate the interaction of the site and how content (both visual and text-based) might look on mobile dimensions. I intentionally used fonts and colors very different from the Jawbone brand's so that in meetings we could all focus on the interactivity of the layouts, instead of harping on graphics.</p>
		<p>With these wireframes, I demonstrated the basic navigation of the site, with a special emphasis on getting buy-in from the team on the structure of the top nav and the footer, which would be accessible on any page.</p>

		<p>Sample low-fidelity wireframe for a product page</p>

		<p>The wireframes reflected some best practices for mobile usability:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Homepage should offer a minimal list of links, prioritized for user needs</li>
			<li>No breadcrumbs (if you need them, it's a sign your site is too deeply layered)</li>
			<li>Links should be obvious</li>
			<li>Tap area should be at least 30px2</li>
			<li>Not using technology that's not universally supported (e.g.,  java, javascript, Flash, frames, auto-refreshes)</li>
			<li>A button to "scroll to top" appears on longer pages</li>
			<li>Incredibly minimal and concise copy</li>
		</ul>

		<p>And though these best practices weren't relevant to the first release of the mobile site, these are still useful to know:</p>
		<ul>
			<li>Minimize number of embedded images for quicker loading times</li>
			<li>Minimize input needed for essential fields (e.g., use zip code instead of city & state)</li>
			<li>Use smart defaults for lists</li>
		</ul>
	</div>
